An alternate approach is to use the Azure Databricks Delta Lake connector directly in ADF. In this design, the ADF Copy Activity connects to Databricks and reads the managed Gold Delta table using its catalog, schema, and table name, so we do not need the table’s internal ADLS path. We apply a Batch ID or modified-timestamp filter to select only the incremental records and copy them into a Synapse staging table. After staging reconciliation and duplicate-key validation, ADF calls a stored procedure to update existing records and insert new records into the final warehouse table. Finally, we update the warehouse watermark.
This approach avoids maintaining a separate Parquet export folder and is simpler for standard loads. However, it depends on Databricks compute during data movement. For very large or recovery-sensitive loads, we may prefer a batch-specific Parquet export because it provides a reusable checkpoint for Synapse retries.



RECOMMENDED-Export managed Gold data to ADLS, then load Synapse
WHY-
Better restartability: If the Synapse load fails, reuse the existing Parquet export instead of reading the Gold table again.
Clear batch checkpoint: Each folder represents one Batch ID and business date.
Easier reconciliation: Compare exported rows with Synapse staging rows.
Better troubleshooting: You can inspect exactly what was sent to Synapse.
Load isolation: Synapse receives only the current incremental batch.
No dependency on managed-table internals: ADF and Synapse never need the managed Gold table’s physical path.
Suitable for large production loads: Parquet is compressed and optimized for analytical processing.
Controlled recovery: Partial staging data can be deleted by Batch ID and reloaded from the same export.
Storage is manageable: Keep exports temporarily—for example, seven days—and remove them through an ADLS lifecycle policy.
